        "p": "When diving into the specifics of wall clock Vastu, several nuanced questions frequently arise. Here are some of the most common inquiries to help you refine your spatial energy. \n\nQ1: Can I hang a clock above the main entrance door of my house or office?\nAnswer: No, according to Vastu Shastra, you should never hang a clock directly above any doorway, especially the main entrance. A door is a portal for energy entering and exiting. Placing a clock above it metaphorically implies that your time, opportunities, and wealth are constantly walking out the door. It also creates a subconscious feeling of being rushed or pressured for anyone who passes underneath it, which can elevate stress levels and disrupt the peaceful energy of the space.\n\nQ2: What is the best shape for a wall clock to enhance positive energy?\nAnswer: The round shape is universally considered the most auspicious for a wall clock. A circle has no beginning and no end, symbolizing continuous flow, wholeness, and eternity. It resonates with the element of space and helps in smoothing out harsh energies within a room. Square or rectangular clocks are also acceptable, particularly in office environments, as they represent the earth element and bring stability and structure. However, clocks with sharp, irregular, or aggressive points should be avoided, as they can emit 'poison arrows' of harsh energy.\n\nQ3: I received a beautiful antique clock as a gift, but it doesn't work. Can I keep it for decorative purposes?\nAnswer: From a strict Vastu perspective, keeping a non-functioning clock is highly detrimental, regardless of its aesthetic or sentimental value. A stopped clock is a powerful symbol of dead time and stagnant energy. It can block your progress and invite lethargy into your life. If you truly wish to keep the antique piece, you must have the internal mechanism repaired so that it functions correctly. If repair is impossible, it is better to part ways with the item rather than let it anchor negative, stagnant energy in your living space.\n\nQ4: Is it okay to keep a clock running a few minutes fast?\nAnswer: Yes, keeping a clock running one to three minutes fast is generally considered acceptable and even beneficial by some Vastu practitioners. It subconsciously programs the mind to be ahead of schedule, promoting punctuality and a proactive attitude. However, never let a clock run behind the actual time, as this signifies delays, missed opportunities, and a tendency to live in the past."
